<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-11-27T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-11-27T05:00:00-05:00" n="407" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d407">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Outer Mongolia/41: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-27T18:00:00+08:00">November 27, 1935—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 27—8:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>183. Following telegram has been received from the Consul General at
                            Harbin.</p>
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“52. November 27, noon. The Japanese Consulate General has confirmed
                                press reports that the Manchuli conference has broken down and that
                                the delegates are leaving. Apparently no agreement of any nature was
                                reached. In a statement the Hsinking Foreign Office laid the
                                responsibility for failure on Outer Mongolia and found ‘no
                                alternative but to act freely in the future’.”</p>
                        </quote>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
